Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]

In[241]:
# Filtering rows where the rating is not given
df_rated = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy()
# Convert rating to integer type
df_rated['rating'] = df_rated['rating'].astype(int)

# Rating count per restaurant
df_rating_count = df_rated.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].count().reset_index()

# Step 3: Filter for restaurants with rating count > 50. Condition 1
df_50_count = df_rating_count[df_rating_count['rating'] > 50]

# Merging df_50_count with df_rated to get the restaurants with count > 50
df_merge_rating_50 = pd.merge(df_rated, df_50_count[['restaurant_name']], on='restaurant_name')

# Calculating the mean rating for each restaurant in the filtered list
df_mean_rating_4 = df_merge_rating_50.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].mean().reset_index()

#Filter for restaurants with an average rating greater than 4. Condition 2
restaurants_criteria = df_mean_rating_4[df_mean_rating_4['rating'] > 4].sort_values(by='rating', ascending=False)

# Print the restaurants that fulfill the criteria
print(" Restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer are:")
print(restaurants_criteria)

1          Blue Ribbon Sushi  4.219178

Observations:

  • The restaurants that fulfill the criteria (rating count more than 50 and average rating greater than 4) to get the promotional offer are: The meatball shop, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, Shake Shack, Blue Ribbon Sushi. All of them have a rating count more than 50 and average above 4.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[245]:
# Write the code here

#Filter the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars
df_cost_more_20 =  df[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20].copy()
#Filter the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars and less or equal than 20
df_cost_more_5 = df[(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (df['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20)].copy()

# Calculating the charge of 25% or 15% accordingly 
revenue1= (df_cost_more_20['cost_of_the_order']*0.25).sum()
revenue2= (df_cost_more_5['cost_of_the_order']*0.15).sum()
#Calculating total revenue
revenue_total = revenue1 + revenue2
print(revenue_total)

6166.303

Observations:

The net revenue generated on all the orders given in the dataset is 6166.3 dollars.

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]

In[248]:
# Write the code here

#Adding new column to the dataframe df to store delivery time + preparation time
df['total_time'] = df['food_preparation_time']+ df['delivery_time']
#Filtering the number of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order 
number_orders_more_60 = len(df[df['total_time']>60])

#Percentage 
print('The percentage of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed is', 
      round((number_orders_more_60/len(df))*100,2), '%')
# Deleting the column created 
del df['total_time']

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

  • The number of orders placed on weekends is much higher than during weekdays, more than double.
  • Delivery time is shorter during weekends than during weekdays, this can be explained by the fact that there may be a reduction in city traffic on non-working days.
  • Shake shack is the most popular restaurant, it has recieved the larger number of orders followed by The Meatball shop.
  • The most popular cuisines during weekends and weekdays are American and Japanese.
  • The most frequent cuisine is American with 30.8% followed by Japanese with 24.8% and Italian cuisine 15.7%. It seems that these 3 cuisines have about 70% of Foodhub's order number.
  • Around 39% of the orders have not been rated and around 30% are rated with 5 score.

Recommendations:

  • Foodhub should incorporate more American, Japanese and Italian restaurants to continue attracting customers as these 3 cuisines are the most popular.
  • Foodhub should pay more attention to developing strategies for all customers to take satisfaction surveys in order to have a clear picture of how to improve or where they are doing a great job. In addition, in order to identify a pattern in what is failing, questions related to delivery time, food preparation time, food quality and food presentation should be included.
  • To increase the number of orders during the weekdays, promotional offers should be included.
  • As the number of orders is higher during the weekends, FoodHub must ensure that it has enough staff to deliver all orders without any setbacks.
  • Foodhub must investigate the reason why customers are giving low ratings to tackle the root problem.
  • Around 10,54% of the total of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered. Foodhub should try to minimize the time to maintain customer satisfaction. It should contact the restaurants to establish the maximum preparation times and with the delivery people the maximum delivery times, thus seeking improvement in each of the instances.
  • Establishing maximum or standard times helps each of the parts of the supply chain adjust to achieve them.
  • Foodhub should talk to Spanish and Vietnamese restaurants to include promotional offers and attract more customers, these two cuisines being the least popular.
  • Foodhub should continue to encourage orders from customers' favorite restaurants such as Shake Shack and The Meatball Shop by providing increased visibility and promotional codes after certain purchases.
